<ul class="org-ul">
<li>This was by far the most enlightening OSHER class I have taken. John Alison is an excellent</li>
</ul>
<p>
teacher and was able to make this most complex of subjects relatable &#x2026; if not always totally
comprehensible. I am sorry I missed his previous course on the history of particle physics,
and hope that he gives it again so I can catch it the next time. I should qualify my answer on
his ability to engage class participants: while he did not go out of his way to draw the audience
in (that is, he did not ask questions of the audience), he was extremely kind and accepting of
all the questions asked of him, which created a very welcoming atmosphere that perhaps
passively encourages audience participation by not intimidating questioners. And, truth be told,
there were so many question asked by the audience along the way, and he took each one
graciously and carefully, that had he also asked questions of the audience he would have had
little time to actually present his material &#x2026;. which would have been a shame. The lab tour
was a great part of the course - it really communicated in ways I didn't previously appreciate
just how big physics is done, and how academics willingly allow themselves to be cogs in a
machine in order for very high level research to be done by a global network.
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Phenomenal teacher. Was able to take ridiculously complicated concepts and simplify them</li>
</ul>
<p>
down to my level, which was pretty low. I wish he would teach other classes and explain
relativity and superstring theory, etc.
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Very interesting. Right level of detail for this type of course</li>

